I retired two years ago after working as a nurse for 30 years. I spent three decades taking care of other people. I wanted time for myself. I joined a pottery class on Saturdays, started going to the gym, made plans with friends I hadn't seen in years because I was always too tired or too busy. But Brooke didn't care about any of that. She'd text me Friday night saying, Austin needs you tomorrow at 8:00am, and then show up with him still in pajamas. When I said I had plans, she'd guilt trip me. He's your grandson. I've been there 2 years without issues. Then my boss handed me a project spreadsheet. Update the status column by end of shift problem. It was entirely color coded. Red meant urgent, yellow meant in progress, green meant complete. To me, it all looked like murky brownish gray. I pulled him aside. I can do this but I'm color blind. Can you send a version with labels instead of just colors? His face went cold. Are you refusing to do your job? No, I'm asking for accommodation so I can do it correctly. Two hours later, I had a formal write up for insubordination. I filed a complaint with HR requesting it be removed and asking for reasonable accommodation. I brought documentation from my eye doctor. The HR rap Bridget listen to everything. Then she smiled. I have the perfect solution. Use our tuition reimbursement to take take a remedial art class at the community college. I stared at her. A remedial art class? Yes. So you can finally learn your colors. She said it like color blindness was just failure to study in kindergarten. I tried explaining it's a genetic condition and affecting the cones in my eyes. She just kept smiling and nodding the right up. Stayed. Three months later, still colorblind. I was working my usual Shift four PM to midnight, making sure all systems stayed running. During the holidays, they cut staffing so that week between Christmas and New Years, it was just me in the building. Well, me and Dennis, the security guard in the lobby. December 28th. Eleven fifty eight PM I'm counting down the last two minutes when the door opens and my coworker Brielle walks in. She's supposed to take over the overnight shift alone until 8:00am. But the second she steps through the door, high pitched beeping starts from her insulin pump. Her face goes white. No, no, no. She's frantically checking it. I'm out. Completely out of insulin. Brielle's type 1 diabetic. She wears a pump clip to her belt that delivers insulin. Throughout the day, I'd seen it beep during lunch breaks, just little reminders, but never like this. Never this urgent screaming alarm. I have to go home right now, she said. Already turning my backup supplies in my fridge. If I don't get it in 30 minutes, I'm going into diabetic shop. How far is your house? 23 minutes each way. Her hands were shaking. I called my husband, but he's 40 minutes out. Here's the thing. Company policy was crystal clear. The network center could never be unstaffed. Someone had to be physically present at all times. If we both left, we both be fired immediately. But if she stayed and went into shock with nobody to help, she could die. Go. I said, I'll stay. Until you get back. Tears formed in her eyes. Thank you. I'll drive as fast as I can. The second she left, I called my supervisor voicemail, called the manager on duty voicemail, called the emergency operations line voicemail because nobody checks that during holidays. Rial made it back in 47 minutes, hit traffic. When she walked back in, pump refilled and working, she apologized repeatedly. I told her I do it every time. Next afternoon I.

voice_to_text: When did the pick me girl go too far? Junior year. This girl, Brielle, made everything about her and I mean everything. She'd cry over those Brielle Mclachlan puppy commercials at lunch, full on sobbing with her head on the table. She'd scream random things in the hallway just to see who'd turn around. I tried to ignore her, but we were both in choir so I couldn't escape complete. Then came the spring concert. Twenty minutes before showtime, all 100 of us were on the risers doing final rehearsals. The auditorium was packed with early parents finding seats, programs, wrestling that pre show energy. Brielle was front row center. Obviously. She always made sure she got the spotlight positions. Suddenly the side door opened and Brielle's mom walked in. Not rushed, just purposeful. She went straight to our director, Mr Ford, and whispered something in his ear. He nodded, looked at Brielle and called her name over the microphone. Brielle, can you come down, please? The entire choir went silent. Brielle climbed down from the risers, her heels clicking on the stage floor. Her mom pulled her aside, leaned in close and said maybe three sentences. That's when Brielle screamed. Not a gasp, not a cry, a full horror movie blood curdling scream that Echoed off every wall in that auditorium. Parents and the audience stood up. Some of the freshman girls started crying just from hearing it. Brielle took off running for the exit, but she only made it about 20 feet before her legs gave out. She collapsed right there on the auditorium floor, wailing like someone had ripped her heart out. Oh, my god. Oh, my god. Oh, my god. Oh, my god. Over and over and over. Her mom rushed over, grabbed her by the elbow and practically dragged her out through the side door. The whole thing took maybe 90 seconds, but it felt like an hour. Mr Ford stood there frozen. Nobody knew what to do. Finally, he cleared his throat and said, let's, let's take five minutes. The second we got backstage, everyone pulled out their phones. Our group chat exploded with messages. Someone texted Brielle directly. She responded. Twenty minutes later, nothing will ever be the same. Then why couldn't it have been me? Then she stopped responding entirely. Words spread fast.

voice_to_text: My parents were furious when they Learned we bought a new house and called a selfish. So my husband threw them out. But what they said next changed everything. My parents always treated me like the family servant while my brother got everything. Growing up, I'd mow lawns while he played video games. I do laundry while he hung out with friends. When I complained, my dad would say I was being ungrateful. I left at 19 and never looked back. I met my wife in grad school. She saw how my family treated me and was horrified when I told my parents we were getting engaged at 25. They said she was beneath me, that I was making a mistake. We got married anyway, just her family there. They moved to Florida about eight years ago. Honestly, our relationship only works with distance. We text sometimes, but it's always tense. Last month, my wife and I bought our dream condo, two bedrooms downtown, everything we wanted. We were thrilled but kept it quiet from my parents. They're paying for a storage unit nearby and I knew exactly what would happen if they found out. As far as they knew, we rented a studio near my wife's office. Yesterday afternoon, I was working from home when my college buddy Ryan knocked. Behind him were my parents running like they pulled off a surprise. Ryan ran into them at target and thought it'd be nice to bring them over the moment They walked in and saw our open concept living room, the granite counters, the balcony view. My mom's smile died. She looked around slowly, face getting redder. Then she exploded. She screamed about how selfish we were, all this space and we never offered to help with. She yelled about how we've been getting along so well lately. Why would I lie? She said. I was sneaky and ungrateful, just like always. I stood there frozen. Ryan looked horrified. My mom kept going. Family helps family. You clearly don't care about us. That's when my wife came home. She walked in, saw my mom gesturing wildly, saw my face and her expression hardened. She set down her bag. Stop yelling in our home. My dad quiet until then, face bright red. Your home, he spat. You mean the home my money helped buy? The room went silent. I felt my stomach drop. I turned to face my parents. What money? My mom's angry expression shifted to something smug. She crossed her arms. We've been sending your brother $1,500 every month for eight years to help you both. We assumed he was splitting it like we asked. My wife's jaw dropped. I couldn't breathe. voice_to_text: My family didn't care when I became a lawyer until my brother got arrested. Then all of a sudden they wanted me again. After I passed the bar exam to become a lawyer. I texted my family the date and time of my swearing and ceremony. My dad replied saying he couldn't make it because my brother Silas had a golf tournament at the same day. My mom said she'd be at the tournament too. Silas sent a laughing emoji and wrote, it's just a ceremony. You already passed. We'll celebrate later. I stared at my phone and typed back, understood. The ceremony was beautiful and I sat there in a room full of new lawyers with their families cheering and taking pictures. I was alone. The woman next to me had her entire extended family there and they kept apologizing for being too loud. I told them it was fine and tried not to cry. Afterwards, the law firm I joined took photos of all the new associates for their website and newsletter. I smiled in my professional headshot and pretended I wasn't heartbroken. My boss pulled me aside and said, where's your family? I wanted to meet them. I said they couldn't make it. And he looked confused but didn't push. I started working criminal defense and I was good at it, really good. I won cases that senior partners said were unwinnable. I worked 80 hour weeks and built a reputation. My family never asked about my Work. At Thanksgiving, my dad spent an hour talking about Silas's promotion at his sales job. And when I mentioned I'd won a major case, he said, that's nice and change the object. Silas asked if I was dating anyone. And when I said I was too busy with work, he said, you're always going to be too busy. That's your problem. My mom nodded and said, he's right. You need balance. I said, I have balance. I'm building a career. My dad laughed and said, Silas has a career and still makes time for family. Maybe you should take notes. On Christmas, my dad gave Silas an expensive watch and gave me a gift card to target. When I opened it, Silas smirked and said, at least you can buy yourself something nice. I left early and my mom texted me later saying I'd ruined Christmas by being dramatic. I stopped going to family dinners. After that, my dad would text saying I was being distant and I needed to make more effort. Didn't respond. My mom called once and said, your father is hurt that you won't come around anymore. Family is supposed to forgive. I said, family is supposed to show up and hung up. Six months after my swearing in ceremony, I got a call from my dad at 2 in the morning. He said, Silas has been arrested. You need to come to the police station right now. I was exhausted from a long day. In court. But I got dressed and drove 40 minutes to the station. Silas had gotten into a bar fight and assaulted someone badly enough to send them to the hospital. The charges were aggravated assault and he was looking at serious prison time. My dad grabbed my arm when I walked in and said, you have to fix this. You're a lawyer. You can make this go away. I said, I'm a criminal defense attorney. I don't make things go away. I defend people in court. He said, so defend him. He's your brother. I looked at Silas sitting in the holding cell and he wouldn't even look at me. My dad said, we're family. You owe us this. I said, I owe you this. Where were you six months ago when I got sworn in? My dad said, this is.
